<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06209079 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06209079 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  SF-BAY-AREA; ETHNIC; EMPLOYEE; EMPLOYMENT; DISCRIMINATION; SURVEY  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Concerned about the number of workers of Asian and Pacific Island ancestryreporting discrimination on their jobs, members of a San Jose community groupsaid this week they plan an extensive study of the problem in the South Bay.;   The discrimination complaints emerged during an informal, non-scientificstudy in May by the group, Asian Americans for Community Involvement, whichinterviewed about 50 privately employed workers at a business convention inthe South Bay. Among the survey's findings:  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Local  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  JOB BIAS PROBLEM SURFACESASIANS REPORT DISCRIMINATION  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     (check) Asked if they'd ever been denied a job because of their race, 19percent said &quot;yes,&quot; and another 22 percent replied &quot;maybe.&quot;;    (check) Askedif they feared their race might hurt their chances for future promotion, 22percent answered &quot;yes&quot; and another 37 percent &quot;maybe.&quot;;    (check) Almost 70percent said they knew of at least one other Asian or Pacific Island workerwho believed they had lost a promotion because of their race.;    &quot;There is alot of concern about this,&quot; said Michael Chang, who supervised the study forthe group and is chairman of the Asian/Asian American Studies Department at DeAnza College in Cupertino. &quot;It's a very big issue. A lot of people feelpowerless about it.&quot;;    The group published the data in its July newsletter,along with findings from a recent Mercury News study that showed a relativeshortage of Asian and Pacific Island employees in city and county governmentworkforces, particularly in upper management positions.;    Many people havecalled in response to the newsletter offering to help the group press forbetter job opportunities for Asians and Pacific Islanders, Chang said. Headded that the organization, which offers a variety of health and otherservices to the South Bay's Asian Pacific American community, recently began astudy of job discrimination in private industry and plans a more extensiveattitude survey. It's still undecided how the survey will be conducted.;   Chang said the organization welcomes assistance from others, particularlylocal business executives. &quot;We'd like to get cooperation eventually fromcorporations interested in dealing with these problems in a serious way,&quot; hesaid.;  IF YOU'RE INTERESTED; Anyone interested in the job discriminationstudy can contact Michael Chang at (408) 864-8878. Asian Americans forCommunity Involvement is at 232 E. Gish Road, San Jose, and can be reached at(408) 452-5151.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  STEVE JOHNSON, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910727  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Saturday  </DAY><MONTH>  July  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1B  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  383  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Saturday July 27, 199100209079,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>